<h1>Types of Networks</h1>
<h2>Local Area Networks (LANs)</h2>
<h2>Wide Area Networks (WANs)</h2>



<h1>Open Systems Interconnection Model (OSI)</h1><p>--is a conceptual model that characterises and standardises the communication functions of a telecommunication or computing system without regard to its underlying internal structure and technology</p>
<h2>7. Application Layer</h2>
<h2>6. Presentation Layer</h2>
<h2>5. Session Layer</h2>
<h2>4. Transport Layer</h2>
<h2>3. Network Layer</h2><p>--packets</p>
<h2>2. Data Link Layer</h2><p></p>
<h2>1. Physical Layer</h2><p>--bits</p>

<h2>Physical Topologies</h2>
<p>CSMA/CA = Carrier Sense Multiple Access / Collision Avoidance (wireless networks)</p>
<p>CSMA/CD = Carrier Sense Multiple Access / Collision Detection (wired networks)</p>
<p>Exponential Backoff--used by both ethernet and wireless networks to enable collision avoidance/detection and deconfliction</p>
<h3>Bus Topology (archaic)</h3>
<p>everything is connected by a single bus -- coaxial cable</p>
<h3>Ring Topology (archaic)</h3><p>--exactly what it sounds like. each computer is connected to two computers.</p>
<p>unidirectional or bidirectional</p>
<h3>Star Topology</h3><p>--central device is switch or hub</p>
<p>central device is single point of failure</p>
<h3>Mesh Topology</h3><p>--each device is connected to every other device by separate cabling</p>
<p>used in wide area networks (WANs) for redundancy. Expensive install.</p>


<h1>Note: most networks are a hybrid type of physical topology</h1>


